Lerwick, Shetland}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid3027762 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid2637051\charrsid16072257 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-461\li461\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin461\itap0\pararsid2637051 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 You said you were born in Lerwick, in what year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 I was born in Lerwick, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname date}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Year}{\xmlattrvalue 1906}}
{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Day}{\xmlattrvalue 26}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Month}{\xmlattrvalue 7}}}the twenty-sixth of July 1906{\*\xmlclose}.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 And you lived there for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh about one year.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 And then you came to -?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Yes, my people - my father and mother were staying in Lerwick. My father was working there as a joiner. And - again this was his old home, they didn't like Lerwick, so he came down here - it must have been about the beginning of 1907.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Why do you think he didn't Lerwick?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 He didn't like the town, didn't like the coal and he wanted to go to the fishing. Had a boat at sixern belonged to them 
and he been going to the sea in the sixern before he went to Lerwick. It was where he met my mother. In Lerwick, yes. And - so they came back here and went to the fishing in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 summertime}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  and worked on the croft and as a carpenter or joiner in the wintertime.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 He worked here as a carpenter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Yes, yes, yes. A joiner, making - well he made some farm - he made carts and cartwheels and - and he made spinning wheels. Made a lot of them, especially in the '14-'18 war, there were a great demand for them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 When he was working in Lerwick was he working for a firm?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes, he was working for a - for a firm - the firm there was M.P. Morrison.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Was that the first job that he'd ever had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No, he'd been working on his own before he went to Lerwic
k as a carpenter and it was a friend who got him this job in Lerwick. He had gone to Lerwick sometime before and got a job at the carpenters, he was locally here and his father, his father was a carpenter as well and - this man got my father a job along w
ith him. About the beginning of the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 century}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 , maybe 1902 I'm not very sure about that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 The first job that he would have had would have been as a carpenter?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 In Lerwick, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 But was that the first job he ever had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No, he'd been going to the fishing and just a sort of a handy man probably since he left school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 He really had a variety of jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Was apprenticed to the carpenter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well - not exactly. Apparently he knew so much about it and he'd been working at it tha
t he - I think when - I've heard him say when he started first he was given nearly a full carpenter's wage. He worked for three or four years I'm not sure and I think there were one season while he was still in Lerwick that he went to the fishing in a her
ring boat. Because he preferred the sea to working in the town anyhow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Can you tell me how they got this boat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 How they got it? Well it was built for them. It was - as far as I know it was built in Lerwick this boat. And it was an open sixern to 
start with and after they'd had it for some years they got it decked you know what I mean, a deck. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 
A little small cabin and - from the fore end where they had meals and where they slept if they did sleep, there wasn't really - there wasn't bunks there were must seats along the side. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
But line - line fishing had white fish.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did they go out a long way for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh yes, they've gone - thirty miles I should think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Would he be away for long times?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well - I don't think they ever were away a f
ull week. If they went out on Monday they came - they landed their fish here locally you see and they'd go one time and if they got a lot of fish they'd come back the following day and maybe been home just for a short time and went again and sometimes if 
they hadn't much fish they would stay out all day, maybe two days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 And at a particular time of the year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Yes. From May to - oh September I should think. And then after the fishing season they - you see this fish, they had men working ashore at this fish. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 
The men cleaned the fish and salted it and then, and they looked - they was laid out on the beach to dry in the sun.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 This was here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes, down here not very far away. And - but since that they had better summer weather than we have now 
because you could spread that fish out on the beach, it was a stone - flat stone beach, in the daytime and there was generally an old man who looked after them and they piled them up on the beach and covered them with - with a tarpaulin at night and then 
t
hey had to be finished off after the fishing season and they dried them in a shed, well it was a stone built shed, they called it a bose and they had - hang them up to the rafters and they had a fires that could shift over the floor and they burnt coke. D
ried them off and they packed them and then they were shipped to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Aberdeen{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} or wherever they went to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 So there were quite a lot of people in the village here who were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 fishing}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 well there were - there were - there were several boats fishin
g at that time but my father and this boat, they - they sold this boat about 1914 and he never went fishing after that. Well I think in 1915 he went in a - in a smaller boat for just one season. And he never was at the fishing after that except - oh maybe
, oh for - well a short time for - to catch a few fish.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Was that because of the war do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well - yes, the herring fishing and all was stopped during the war, the '14-'18 war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 You had to have quite a bit of money to build a boat did you, or did they work on the boat themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No, I - the - the boats didn't cost very much then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 You took shares in it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 There were three of them, my two uncles and my father. I don't suppose - I don't suppose when that boat was built first
 it cost much more than twenty pound for the boat - for the hull of the boat. The sails, they had a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 mainsail}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
 and - a jib. Well - canvas is - very costly now but at that time well I - I just don't know how much it would have cost. And then after they had th
is boat - now remember - this boat was built for them in 1894. And sometime - about the beginning of the century, I'm not just sure about that, they got a deck and I think my father helped them, that job, done locally. There were a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 boat builders}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  locally. Yes. And he - he got this boat, my father worked with it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 It's the beach just down there is it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Yes, just about half a mile along the road. Oh but there's not much of a beach there now, it's all gone. There's nothing much left at all, there's an old pier there but.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 There was a pier as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Yes. There was a pier. And then in the wintertime when the - when the fishing season was over they took the boat ashore and hauled it up and it stood up on dry land all the winter. I believe in Febr
uary 1900 there was a very severe gale, a storm, that crossed the road there and damaged some of the boats, standing high - they were standing well up from the sea but - it was always spoken about, the February gale 1900. Did a lot of damage here and dest
royed teaches and all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Then you say in the winter he was working as a carpenter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
He was working as a carpenter or a joiner and of course they - they repaired the fishing gear, they mended the nets and so on but - he was working as a joiner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 By himself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes, by himself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 He never employed anybody?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
No. Just by himself. Yes. Well he made like kitchen dressers and - and beds. You see, there were none of them stuff that you get nowadays that's like then, that's all machine made and
 mass produced. But it was all hand made then. The things that they throw out now I suppose \{BLANK\}
 like that. Then he made - carts and cartwheels. And another thing that used not used now was sledges for sledging peat down from the hills. Horse pulled the
 sledge up empty, they load it with peats and sledge them - the horse pulled them down to the road. And then they were carted home, by horse and cart.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 So did he himself work very much on the croft?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes, he worked on the croft as well. And in the barn in the wintertime and oh there were various jobs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 What would he be doing in the barn in the winter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Well thrashing with a flail and - winnowing the corn and then the - at that time there were a mill there at Quendale that ground the corn i
nto meal and the corn had to be prepared for this, it had to be the - the bere - the bere, what they call the bere, sort of barley, it had to be dried on a kiln on the - in the barn and - cleaned and - and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 carted}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  to - on a cart to the mill and ground there
 and then they went with the cart and brought home the - the meal from the mill. But that mill was there about - well maybe not derelict but it never has been used, still there at Quendale. Quendale, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Can you tell how many beasts there were on the croft?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
How many beasts? Well when I remember first - we had three small ponies, well not just Shetland ponies you know but - I remember they had two for ploughing. And - sheep, well we never kept very many sheep here. The most breeding ewes that I 
can remember was with - about fifteen. And - when I was a boy I don't think they had many more than that. And - maybe two, three - two milking }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 cows}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  and - two year old ones and maybe two calves or - from six to eight at that time. And I don't suppose ever w
e had more than eight, we had seven here a few years ago. But that was October, all the cows had - had their young you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did you fatten them and then sell them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes, we generally went to a cattle sale with one or two, and when a cow's old and
 finished her - having calves and milk then they would feed that one and went along to the cattle sale the auctioneer there. It was a great favourite, cattle sale day when I was going to school and - from 1912 to 1920, then there was two cattle sales each
 
year and we got time off from school to go to this cattle sale and very often - I never came back again in the afternoon from my home but - it didn't always do. Oh yes, the cattle sale commenced about eleven o'clock in the fore noon and - you had - off to
 
- left school maybe from eleven to two, you were supposed to come back again at two and spend the rest of the afternoon, or whenever the cattle sale was finished. And I remember once or twice - some of us went home, we never went back to school. Of course
 we had to go the following day. But that didn't matter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 You say your father met your mother in Lerwick?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did she have any job before they were married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes. My mother belonged to Yell. Her father was a seaman all his life. Went to
 sea when he was a boy fourteen and was in sailing ships until away about the end of last century and then - he was - on some of the - North of Scotland boats for a few years And I think that he retired about - 1905 maybe. You see, my mother's mother died
 
I think about 1900. They had a small croft in Yell but me grandfather was always at sea so they left Yell, left the croft there and came to stay in Lerwick. And it was in a tenement house. That's where my father was staying too you see, there were differe
nt families in the one house and that's where they met. Sometime about 1903, I'm not sure, I've heard it but there's nobody now to tell me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Your mother was working in some job then was she in Lerwick at the time?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes, I think she was servant to 
some - I believe they had a - a business, I'm not very sure about that. I think that - the - gentleman was - I know one thing, he bought cattle. But I think - no, he was a - his son was a - he only died a few years ago but - I don't know if he was, if thi
s man ever come here, he maybe went along buying up cattle, fat cattle. Well a cattle dealer, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 And then they married and came here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 They were married and then - yes, was here until she died. Yes, she-
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 She never went out to work or did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
No, never here, no, never after she married. She had plenty of work to do. With three of us and she had plenty here and working around the - around the croft.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 There were just your father and mother living in the croft or did you have any other relatives?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No, I had an uncle - no, when I remember first my grandfather and grandmother were living and my uncle and two aunts.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 All living here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 They were living in the old room that you see - the roof is falling in now, but the old hou
se where they - where they were living then. My grandfather, he died in 1913. My uncle died in 1920. My grandmother lived on 'til 1930 and then I think she was ninety-two. And my aunt, she lived alone there in the old house until - 1967. Just three years 
back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Not the cottage you pointed out to me further up the hill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh no, not that one, not that one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Down towards the bay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No, it was down here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 On the croft?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 It's on the croft, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 So there were two houses on the croft?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Yes. Yes, well - there were just supposed to be done. That place next door was where my father and mother stayed, well there's three rooms along there. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 How many rooms are there altogether then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Here in the main house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Are the two cottages are they really built together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 All built together. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 But you lived separately?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
We have - yes. My father and mother and the three children, my brother and sister and myself, lived - we had three rooms. And then the old house had three rooms as well. That was an old house with a - with a straw thatched roof.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 This one has a slate roof?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No, it's cedar wood shingles. And - next door, that - my father, he built that in 1907 and he put - he got red cedar shingles from C
anada and that's what they were roofed with. And most of that shingles were on for sixty years. And I renewed them all the last - I had been renewing them for near twenty years but - 1967 I took the last of the old ones off that had - went on in 1907. So 
they were on for sixty years. Red cedar shingles from Canada.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 You said you had one brother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 How much younger than you was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Two years and a half.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 And then a sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Five years younger than myself. Yes. Two years and a half younger than my brother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 I think you said your father was born in 1877?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 1877.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Was your mother the same age?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 She was - my father was born on the twenty-fifth of March 1877. My mother was born on the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 tenth}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  of August 1877 so that was the difference between them. She was a few months younger.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did your mother pay anyone to help in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No, never. Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Would she send out the washing or do that at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 She did it herself. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did she or your father either mend or make the family clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
My father made the clothes many a time, trousers and jackets we were going to school. Yes. Yes. He - he shaped it out, he got the cloth and shaped them, shaped it out and then sewed it on a hand driven sewing m
achine. Machine with a handle, put it one the table. Oh yes. But not - not all our clothes. Our best clothes were bought and - well the clothes that he made we generally wore about the home. Sometimes he made a jacket that we went to school with but - gen
erally the clothes we went to school with were bought from the shop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 In Lerwick?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well no, there were local shops that stocked that stuff in, you don't have that now. There were a little }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 grocery shop}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  just about quarter of a mile - less than a quarter of a mile along the road here. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 And there was an old cobbler's about a quarter of a mile on. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
And he made the boots. And - then there was another little shop - oh a bit farther along the road, just - a little bit up passed where that new school is built 
now and there was a shop and a smithy, a blacksmith there. A blacksmith was shodding horses, making - shoeing horses and - and then there was a baker a little bit up past that. There's none of that now at all, it's all gone and I don't know whether it's a
ny better now or was then, certainly there's more money now and - they had a hard time but they were I think more contented.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 So your father didn't make any of the shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No. He - he mended them but I can't remember him ever making us shoes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did your mother make clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No, she - she knitted - she'd knit quite a lot but - she didn't make any clothes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 In the house did your father help with any of the jobs like cleaning or cooking or washing-up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well sometimes maybe a little cooking, I never remember him washing-up, except in an emergency.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 What about lighting fires?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 My mother always got up first in the morning and had the fire going before - yes, and a cup of tea, before any of us got up. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 But he would do the decorating?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh yes. Painting and paperhanging.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Would he help you children dress or that kind of thing, put you to bed, anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No, it was generally my mother who put us to bed. And dressing, well as far as I can remember I co
uld always get on my own clothes from I was very young. Oh yes, I can remember when we were - Sunday when we were going to church or Sunday school the mother getting on with it. We had little coat, hat, bow ties at that time. And she used to put them on f
or us and - about all I think. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 Very often she would comb our hair, we were a bit maybe - she would comb our hair for us. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
We used to go out with a hat and respectable.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did you ever go out with your father by yourself without your mother as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh with me father? Oh yes, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 I suppose you went around helping him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes. Yes, as a boy. And - he -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 So you saw a lot of him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 
He - when he was making that spinning wheel - well from the time I was about maybe eleven years old I had a great delight in working that old wood turning lathe. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
And - he used to have to - bit of wood ready for spokes or - legs and I would come home from school at night and - and turn this for him. Maybe like a spoke he had one turned for a sample 
and then well I copied this one for measurements and - and the thickness and turned it down on the wood turning later, and shaped it and - that's what I make this - but, oh yes, I helped him quite a lot then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 What other ways would you help in the house as a boy, or were you helping more with your father's work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
I can't say, maybe I - put some fuel on the fire, but that was about all. I was going to school and come home at night and we were generally off playing about some - somewhere.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Was your sister expected to help in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No, not very much. No. My mother did it all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 So you really had quite a lot of time to play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh yes, we - of course one time when we came home from school your school clothes had to come off and you
 had to put on your - old rags to play around in because we were in everything. Knocked over, stone dykes and running around and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 They didn't mind what you did as long as you were in the old clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No. Not if we had the old clothes on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 What time did you have to be in to go to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
No particular time - well when we were very young we came to bed maybe eight o'clock but as you got older it always got later until we were staying up 'til the - old people went to bed. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 When was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Well, at that time - they went to bed earlier than they do now. Generally we'd all be in bed by half past ten. Because we were going to school. And my father and mother, they always went to bed about half past ten as long as they lived. But we 
were young, grown up and we've been up maybe twelve o'clock at night. After we left school like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 You said there were three rooms in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did you use two as bedrooms?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes, two as bedrooms and just a living room, that was the kitchen and all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Nobody had to sleep downstairs in the living room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 You didn't have a bathroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No, we didn't have a bathroom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 You used the kitchen did you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No, just the kitchen. Well we did have a small place where we had a wash had basin and so on. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 That was when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Yes, we had a small place to - well it was just a - what we called a washstand with a - a basin on top and then - you see we didn't have any water her then. We had to carry the water in pails from the well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Was that far?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No, it wasn't far, it was only a few yards but some weren't as lucky as we were. They had to carry it a long way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 That meant you had to be very careful with how much water you used?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh
 we could use as much water as we liked only when you had to go to the well for you with your pail. As I said, we hadn't so far to go but - some people had a - a fair distance to carry it, maybe two hundred yards, maybe more.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 It wasn't a well that ran dry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
No. Always water - unless it was a very dry summer, we don't get that sort of summer now. But we did then sometimes. Yes. Yes. So we had to be careful with - there was a - a stream about four hundred yards from the house. It never dried and it 
was good clear water. Sometimes in a very dry summer we would have to go maybe for a week, get water from this stream. Well it wasn't very often. I mean we'd get a - some rain and then the well filled up again, spring started flowing. But - we were never 
-
 though I have heard way back, oh maybe a hundred years, a very dry summer where the wells all dried up but they had to go a long distance for their water. Now you see there are - every house has the water - inside. But that - well, since the last war - 1
945, a great change you know, we - before that we didn't have electricity. We didn't have the water in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Was there a regular day when your mother had a washday and you had clean clothes to put on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 We always - yes. Clean clothes every week, we always had clean clothes. We had a washday - well she had a little to wash every day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did you eat in the kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did you ever eat in the other room?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No, very seldom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 When would that be if you did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well - the only time that I can think about was when you were maybe not well go to bed for - but that was all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 What sort of equipment was there for cooking, was it the open grate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh that was - that was my grandfather and grandmother had the open fire, we always had w
hat we called a stove. Was an opening in it and a place for the fire and - and - and heat the kettle and the pots etcetera. Hobs lifted up for the - hob and the kettle and all on top. Done that many a time with - there is a small one there with a door, bu
t it was a bigger one than that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did you all eat together at breakfast or at different times?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Well - we generally all ate together but when we were going to school maybe we had our breakfast before our parents had theirs. We had our breakfast and
 off we went to school and when we were out of the road then they would sit down in peace and have theirs. And then, there were no school meals, we took our piece and a bottle of milk. Piece of bread and a bottle of milk. Well, in the wintertime, then we 
g
ot cocoa in the school. Cocoa, yes. We - had to take a tin of cocoa and some sugar to school. It was all - everybody's was put in a cupboard there and - and there was a big pot boiled on top, there was a stove in the school much the same as we had here at
 
home but only a bit bigger, and - the - the pot was boiled up, the water was boiled up on top of this fire and then all this cocoa was stirred up in this container, I forget what it was, I think it was a big enamel bucket but - and they boiled water and p
o
ured in and then it was - was in a big jug with a big - earthenware jug and you went with your little mug and got it filled up. The sugar and everything was stirred up together. And then you had your bread there and - that was the wintertime. But in the s
ummertime we just - had a bottle of - we'd plenty of milk, put milk in a bottle and we got out and way up the sand and sat down somewhere. Then we got our meal - we got a proper meal when we came home at - in the evening.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 What time would the breakfast be then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Well - while - I should say about half past eight because the school - then in the summertime - no, in the summertime it was half past nine and in the winter at quarter to ten. Summertime you went to school at half past nine and you had a - 
a came out about eleven o'clock for maybe ten minutes, then went back in school again. Then you had an hour for lunch or - this bread and milk you had, from twelve to one. Then you were in at one o'clock, then we had our interval again at three for about 
t
en minutes. And then you - you finished at four. That's in the summertime. In the wintertime I think you only had a half - half an hour for your midday meal, I'm not sure about that, yes, I suppose you had a - ten minutes interval in the forenoon but I do
n't know in the afternoon, I'm not sure about that. I can't - I can't remember.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 What would you eat at breakfast at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well generally we had porridge and milk and then maybe bread and marmalade or something and a cup of tea. For breakfast.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 when you were at home, what about the midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
When we were home? Well when I was a boy going to school it was mainly potato soup and fish and sometimes mutton. You - a crofter then would maybe slaughter one of his fat sheep and then you had so
me mutton. Sometimes you had beef. They used to - maybe two or three crofts would slaughter a fat cow and sort of share it out. And - salt it down. Mind there were no fridges and deep freezers then, you had to salt it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 So most of the meat would be salted?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Yes. It had to be salted. If you want to keep it any time. Of course - fish. Well they salt fish and salt herring but - occasionally when the weather was fine they would - some of them would go off and get - fresh herrings. Oh we never were hung
ry, not here anyhow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 And then you had an evening meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
We had our tea. When - well when we came home from school then we had a proper meal, it could be anything - always generally potatoes and - maybe fish, maybe - fried. Another thing we had eggs, we had - oh yes, we always eggs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 You kept your own hens?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Yes. And we had ducks. We don't keep any ducks now but we used to have ducks eggs. I think they're best. We used to have them sometimes boiled, sometimes fried. Oh yes, we - I never was hungry. I never was hungry at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Most of the food came off the croft?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Yes, most of it come off the croft, even the - while we - we had oatmeal ground at the old mill at Quendale that I was telling you about, then the bere and the - the oatmeal for porridge in the morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did your mother bake her own bread?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes, she baked her own bread. Oh yes, that was very good. Pancakes occasionally and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did she make jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes, rhubarb jam. That was just about - we always - that - a
bout whether rhubarb is a fruit or a vegetable. You call rhubarb - oh yes, we always had rhubarb jam. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did she bottle any fruit or vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well we didn't have any - vegetables.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 You didn't grow vegetables except potatoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Potat
oes and turnips and maybe a few carrots. That was about all. Oh and cabbage. Oh yes, we had cabbage too, yes. Certainly we did, always cabbage.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did she make any wines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No, never made any wines.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did the people round here do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No. B
ut I believe the old people - before my time - used to brew their own ale. I don't know how they did it but they did it - but before my time they did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did they have hops?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well they got the hops, I suppose so. Yes. They called it Shetland ale but - I never tasted it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 What about medicines did she make any medicines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
No, there was generally patent medicines you could buy out of the shop like - well I can't remember having castor oil but you've got some stuff that I can remember, he called
 it cedar syrup. I don't know what it was for, if you got a cold. Oh there's things sometimes in an old medical - sulphur, brimstone and - and sugar mixed up. You know, in a - in saucer and a teaspoon and you - I don't know what it was good for or - but w
e
 - we - as we went along we never had very much illness. Except the usual things that you get, I had whooping cough before I can remember, I had chickenpox when I was about five years old, the school - the school we went to there were chickenpox in the sc
hool it was going for three weeks, and I got off very well there 'cos I had one of the spots that was all, but the school closed for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14229023\charrsid12668771 three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  weeks.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 They don't take that so seriously now do they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh not at all. And I never had measles until I was way over twenty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did you ever buy any tinned or dried vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 There weren't any on the market at that time. No. I never remember -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did you buy tinned meats?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes, corned beef, what did they call it now, we used to have it like at - 
Fray Bentos is it. Fray Bentos. That was corned beef, Fray Bentos I think it was. Yes, we had that occasionally but - not very often and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 What about rabbits?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes. At one time there were plenty of rabbits around here and we used to snare them. I
 remember me father used to set a snare to get rabbits and - and skin them and we had - oh they were good. And my brother was a great rabbit hunter. I did do a little of it but - not very much. I sometimes caught one or two but I wasn't much of a poacher,
 I didn't like taking the skins off them. But my brother was good and oh we used to have them. But - not now. Because }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 myxamatosis}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  came - the rabbits here, quite a few rabbits here but not how it used to be.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Would it be on the croft that you caught them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Yes. Some on the croft and - there were no restrictions, you could go on the - on the croft or where - generally you the rabbits that burrows where - in the sand. Well there's not much sand in this croft. But - the croft further along was more sand
 in and - you get them there and they had their runs and set the snares out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did they mind you doing it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Not at all. Well there was one or two as did but - generally they never bothered. In fact some of them were glad of you - you - you do snare rabbits because they're a bit of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 nuisance}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  really, the turnips and the grass and - yes, there were one or two that checked out but - but there's none of that now. Not much anyhow because of - since - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 myxamatosis}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  came about - came all over Britain about the same time. Oh we got it here, yes. One of them fell just down here, it was an awful - yes, }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 their}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  eyes all poking out and they couldn't see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 When you were having your meals were you allowed to talk as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh sure, we talked - talked, yes. We did anyhow.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Were you allowed to choose what you lived to eat out of what was cooked or did you have to eat a bit of everything?;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh it was only - eat a bit of everything. We always like it. Yes. Used to go outside and come in hungry and - oh 
- come on mum, I'm hungry. Get a piece of bread and jam any time of day. And my grandfather, if I went to me grandmother next door and she give you a bowl of milk and a - a piece of bannock. It was all right. Sometimes we used to take this bannoch and bre
ak it up in the milk and then sup it with a spoon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 You could ask for more if you wanted it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 What did your parents feel if you left food uneaten on the plate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well - you left something uneaten well there's something wrong w
ith you and - but that didn't happen very often, it just was left over and maybe the hens got it or the cat or the dog, some cats and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 But there wasn't }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 a great}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  fuss about anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh no fuss at all. No fuss here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Were they strict about the way you held your knife and fork?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Not really. They told you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 it\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  all right maybe at home but if you went out among people you have to do things the proper way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Could you bring a book or a toy or anything to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh I've s
een me reading a book at the table, toys, well I can't remember that, I must have been very small. The others had toys, some of them homemade, little boat with a - little pond up here at the back where we sailed our little boats and - then - made our own 
toys. Throw up a brick and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Could you leave when you'd finished or did you have to wait for everybody to finish?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well our parents weren't very fussy about that. Just - well we picked it up as we went along. That was how we - we had a fairly free
 and easy life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did you have set places where you always sat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh yes. Always the same place at the table. Ooh - The food wouldn't taste proper if you
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 And your mother would serve up the food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Would she serve your father first and then the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 I suppose so. That was generally how it was done.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 When your younger brother was very small, was he made to eat separately or did you always have them with you at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 They were always at the table when they could eat for themselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Would you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 say that}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  your mother was an easy person talk to then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh most certainly, she was one of the best.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 And she showed affection to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 If you were worried about something you'd tell here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Tell her. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 What about your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 He was just the same Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 How would you say they expected you to behave towards them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 I never heard any complaints. Never. Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did they bring you up to behave towards your brother and sister in any particular way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Well, yes, they did but we had many quarrel among a ourselves, when my brother thought I'd got something better than him and he didn't like it and - that was - just kids mind you. Oh I suppose you get that all through life with any -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 If another child hurt you would they say that you should hit back or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 That's rather a delicate question, I think if somebody hit you when we }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 
were young}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  we hit back.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 What kind of people do you think your parents hoped that you would become?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well, I don't know, they - I expect they expected much more of than what we turned out to be.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Would you say that they considered certain things important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Aye, to be honest and truthful and - oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 They were very strict about swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Well they didn't like us to swear. I suppose when we grew up so we - we didn't - we - I can't say that now! And - another thing. I'm smoking me pipe nearly all the time, while my father, he smoked his all the
 time and my grandfather he smoked as well and all my uncles, they all smoked a pipe. And when - after I left school I started smoking, I remember the first pipe I had. The first pipe, a new pipe. My mother bought me it on my seventeenth birthday. Before 
t
hat I'd been smoking an old one sometimes belonging to me father and I'll tell you something more. When was going to school I had all sorts of hobbies at home. Maybe making small boats or - sometimes maybe four wheels and this sort of - something like tha
t
. We called it a hobby. Well, I was - had the workshop there and my father never stopped me using his tools. And sometimes I was more interested in what I was doing at home than what I was learning at school. And I made excuses sometimes when I didn't wan
t
 to got to school, played truant or - my teeth was very sore (?) - can't go to school you see. So I didn't go to school. But I remember one morning when I thought I wasn't - I was going - I didn't want to go to school, I was doing something, and - well on
e
 morning in particular I had something that I was doing I didn't want to go to school, and - I didn't have a very good excuse for staying home. Now there was nobody in the kitchen and my father's pipe was lying on the mantelpiece. And I had - I'd tried th
e
 pipe before and it made you feel a bit funny. So I took the pipe, it was before I had my breakfast. And the pipe was fairly strong. And I lit it and I had a good smoke and I didn't feel well and I couldn't eat my porridge. So I stayed home from school al
l day. But about ten o'clock I was all right. That's the sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did your father tell you stories?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 What sort of stories did he tell you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well - he generally told us stories about when he was a boy, and stories that his g
randfather had told him. Sometimes about - mainly - stories about the sea and the fishing and so on. Shetland stories, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 When you had this day off school, what did your parents think about that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh I didn't tell them 'til afterwards, they weren't very strict, we went to school - it wasn't very often that happened, }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 just sometimes}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
 when I was more interested in something I was doing home then. If you missed a day well the teacher asked you the following day what was the matter and you made some 
excuse, probably said you had a headache or toothache or something like that. So didn't know any better or - we never did it two days - you know, two days running of course. And I was - it was mainly myself, and my brother he - was more conscientious than
 
I was as far as the school went. But - see I had so many hobbies when I was going to school. Hobbies at home. And - well, I'd maybe get up a bit early in the morning to do something and then I didn't want to go to school, I would like to carry on with wha
tever I was doing. Maybe making - making a small boat, a toy boat or - or in the winter time maybe making a sledge for he snow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Do you think you were unusual in liking making things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No. I used to make - like in catapults you know, the 
catapults. Well I used to make them for the boys, made a handle out of wood. And they supplied the elastic and of course if the teacher caught you working with that they very often took it from you and shoved it in the fire. Yes. And another thing we used
 
to work with was slings. For throwing stones, you know, you - you - with a leather - with a leather and two strings and you put a stone in and you swing it round your head. We used to work with that but that was - you weren't supposed to work - used that 
at school at all, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Were there any games like hopscotch, that sort of game?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
I - we never played hopscotch but we had - games, well a favourite games was round - what we called rounders. And we played football, just in - not an organised game bu
t we always had a bit of football. And - games - that - I don't know if ever they were played outside of Shetland, like a raining - when it was raining and we couldn't go outside we had a play shed at school and - we had different games that we played in 
t
here, for instance we had one which we called the button. Now - the - children, they sat in a row round, all hand - hold their hands like this and one went round with - his hands in the same position. But he - this is not very good for a recording but - h
e
 had a button, you see, between his hands and he went between one and - and somebody - yes, they opened and he put his hands down between and he would drop this button to some person, you see, and then when he finished the round you had to guess who had t
h
e button. You see, sometimes he would hold his hands for a bit and you would think he was - that was the one who was going to get the button. But it wasn't - he'd gone along and then maybe the one who was going to get the button got it quickly you see and
 
this sort of - put you off and - but if you guessed the right person then - anyone who guessed the right person - the right child like - he went round with the button next time and so on. That was just a game that was played in very - time there were no l
ife much in it, you - just for a rainy day and - well I - I think it's gone, I think it's an old Shetland game, I don't suppose anybody going to school here now knows anything about it, except their parents or grandfathers have told them.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 You played a
round in this free kind of way but I suppose there was sometimes you got up to something your parents disapproved of, would they punish you then if they were angry or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well I can't remember ever being punished. No. Not our parents. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 You don't feel that they were strict?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No, they weren't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Can you remember doing something which you think they were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 annoyed}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh yes, you were told - they would tell you - don't do that again, but I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 But they never actually punished you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
No, I never was punished in me life. Oh we got many a - we had at the school the strap. Oh yes, the strap, got many a - for instance, one time we started carving our names on the - on the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 
desks}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  and on the shed - the shed outside, it was attached 
to the school but the front of it was wood, and we carved our names or our initials on there and the teacher - everybody had them on I think, there were maybe only two and there were about sixty. Well that was altogether, forty - maybe forty boys. But - w
e got - so many licks with the strap for the number of names and besides that we had to pay for putty and paint to fill it up again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 You say you didn't like school really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well - I would - we were sort of - in fine weather in the summertime you w
ere sitting in there and you were looking out the windows and you couldn't go outside, and that was the only thing, as though it was a prison. But I got on all right and passed out at fourteen, we only - then we -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 You couldn't go any further there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No, there }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 were no}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  - well, we could have done, yes, you could get a bursary but I never tried for that. Were only one or two while I was going to school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Was it a master or a mistress?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 It was a mistress nearly all the times that I was at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 You got on well with her?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 All right. And then for a time, my last two years, there was an old seaman who came and teached navigation, once a week, }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 and}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  I - was more interested in that than anything else. And I got on quite well there. But - 
I only had two - two years and then I was fourteen. The - the youngest was twelve you see, you got up in - you got this navigation like when you were twelve years old, twelve to fourteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Would you say that you got your interest in reading from home or from school or just picked it up some }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 other}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Oh no, from school. Oh yes, from school. Oh yes, there was a library in the school, yes, you could get books and things - and besides that there was a public library in the - in the hall and - not fa
r from the school, was open once a week and you could go and borrow books and - oh yes. All the time from I was maybe twelve years old I went regular to that library. Mainly - travel and adventure and - see stories and that sort of thing, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 What did the teacher emphasise as particularly important in ways of behaviour, were they always emphasising punctuality and manners?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes, we were teached that, oh yes. And punctuality is something that I quite approved of. If there was a time set for a cert
ain thing I liked to be there maybe two }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 minutes}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
 before the time, always. And I'm the same yet. The job that I have now - postman, the time to be at the Post Office in the morning is twenty-five minutes to eight and I like to be just about half past seven. 
I'm always there about half past seven. That's about five minutes before the time. Now, the same going to school, if the time was half past nine you went - you had to be at the school in the morning, we were always there - maybe a little bit earlier. Some
 
came late but I can never remember being late for school in the morning. But many a time I was late coming home at night because you had about a mile to walk home, over a mile to walk and there were always something there you lighted by the wayside and - 
see, but - always in time in the morning. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 It was a mixed school, boys and girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Yes. Yes. Only the playground, there were two separate playgrounds. The boys had one and there was a stone wall between the - and the - and the girls at the 
other side. Oh yes. And they had their - the girls had their play shed and - and the boys had their play shed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 So you didn't see them very much then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well, you could shout -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Were the classes mixed?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh yes, the classes were mixed, oh yes, the classes were mixed. When I started going to school there were no boy }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 my age}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
 and I was in a class with six girls. We all came about the same time. And there was - I was - I was - the nearest - was six months younger - nearer - the boy nearest my age was six months younger and the again they were then a year older.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 When you had a birthday would that be different from other days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes. Oh yes, you looked forward to get a birthday present or something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 So you did get presents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh yes. We got - always got something. If it should only be half a crown, half a crown was a lot of money then - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 On your birthdays would you have friends in, you didn't have a special meal or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh no. No. Often that birthday was - well no, my birthday was never at school because it was the 26}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\super\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  of July the summer holidays, so I never had a birthday at school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Were there other special days like for instance Christmas Day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 Oh yes}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 , Christmas Day and New Year's Day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 What sort of things did you do in the family on Christmas Day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well, not very much when I was - we always hang up our stockings on Christmas Eve for Santa Claus, we believed in Santa }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 Claus}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  until you got about you were six or seven years ol
d and then you thought it was - yes. Oh we always hang up our stocking or sock and you get them in the morning, wake up and get the - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 some maybe}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  toys or what we call lucky bags or - or - oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did you have a special Christmas Dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes, mayb
e a - a little bit different from - from the ordinary day. There's more of that now than was in say way back in - from 1910 to 19 - 1920. But since the - Christmas has always been a - sort of an occasion and there was maybe Christmas parties and - dances 
in the local hall. More nowadays than was - back about - well when I was going to school. There were always a Christmas party. But now they'll have a Christmas dance and a New Year's dance and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Were there other special days at that time?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Christmas, New Year, no, that was just about all the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Was there anyone in the family who sang?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 You mean at home? My mother sang - sang a lot, oh yes, she was always singing sort of ballads and - yes, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Would you ever gather together as a family and make music or was that as she worked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
No, we never gathered together just for a - sing-song, no. This district - Dunrossness, there's not so much of that as was farther north, if you get down to Hughie - Hughie Cummings he might tell you so
mething about that. Further north they had more music than here in the - in the - what we call the South End.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 You took up playing music later then, not as a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well I was - yes, I was a schoolboy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 When you first started playing it was later?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh - sometime in the '14-'18 and I was only about twelve years old when the war finished, it was before that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did your father play an instrument?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well - no, he didn't play very much only it was him that had an old fiddle, was lying up 
in the garret and it had all gone to pieces. And a cousin of mine who was a seaman got the - he was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 torpedoed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
 in - maybe more than once in the '14-'18 war, and he got badly smashed up one time and he lost three fingers off his right hand and he had broken 
ribs and he was no longer fit for sea. Well he visited us quite a lot and he got up in the garret and he found this old fiddle and he started glueing it and he put - and he could play. And he got the fiddle all in order, the strings on it and he came with
 a bow and he started playing and oh I thought that was great and then I started tying it myself. Now, I'd been - somewhere between ten and twelve I should think. Before that I - me mother had one of them little old }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 melodeons}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 , she could - yes, and she could
 play that and I tried that but after I got this old fiddle then - I was more interested in the fiddle. And I've kept it up all the time nearly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did your brother play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No, he - he hardly ever tried it. He wasn't very - he wasn't so musical. I su
ppose my father wasn't musical either. Sort of what you would call tone deaf. Yes, you know, he would hum a tune and you could recognise the tune but it was flat sort of, you know what I mean. But my mother was very musical and I think my brother must hav
e taken after me father. He was a bit - tone - well I think tone deaf is a - he could follow a tune but it - was - wasn't - right key, it was kind of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 flat}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 . And - my sister, she was better. I think we must have taken that from - because my mother was very musical. She could sing, yes, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 What about books at home, were there many books in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
We got prize books from the school and there were prize books that me father and uncle had - I read most of them, different - some on travel and I re
member one book that my uncle had got as a prize, Ben Hur, that's been filmed that book Ben Hur by - oh it's about - what happened 2,000 years ago. I remember reading that. And then Robinson Crusoe and that was a great favourite and that was an author the
n
, R.M. Ballantyne who wrote mainly books for boys. And that was the sort of books I used to take out for the library and you'd read a book and you told some other boy about this is a good book and should read that one and he'd taken it next time and maybe
 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4863428\charrsid12668771 vice}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
 versa, he told you about a grand book that he'd read and you'd get one and - yes, that was how we - books, there were plenty of books.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did your parents read?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh yes, me father - I've seen me come home from the library with a - with one or t
wo books and one I was going - wanting to read and he'd got hold of that book and he started to read it and I couldn't get it, very often that happened, oh yes. I'd sit waiting 'til he'd finished this book, until he read it. As soon as he laid down the bo
ok I took it up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did you take any newspapers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Well - there were only two newspapers taken here when I was a boy. That was the local paper, the Shetland Times, and another one that the old people took was the Christian Herald, and that one is stil
l - the - well both papers are still in print, the Christian Herald I haven't seen for a long time but my grandfather used to - to always take this, it was a weekly paper, and he always took this Christian Herald.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No family magazines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No. I cannot - family magazines - no, we didn't take any of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 I don't suppose your father ever read aloud to the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh sometimes he did. But I had an uncle who was good at that. Yes. Yes, he'd come in - he lived in - he lived in - next door with 
my grandfather and grandmother and he used to come in sometimes and I'd get this book, he'd a read a bit - read something for me. Oh he'd sit and read, yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 He'd got a good dramatic way of reading you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes, he was quite good. He was a
 very humorous old man. Yes. He used to - sort of play tricks on us you see. Well he'd - I remember one moonlight night we were out and we saw a ghost in a white sheet and we were a bit scared and this started ghost started running and we started running 
and after a while we discovered it was our uncle with a white sheet. The moonlight - moonlight, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Do you remember a wedding in the family when you were young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Only one. And that was an aunt. She married when I was about seven years old. But sh
e was - the couple had - they were - rather old. She was maybe forty-five and the man she married was I think about ten years older so he'd been about fifty-five. It was a quiet affair but I can remember us getting wedding cake and - yes. But - they weren
't - they didn't marry - they didn't marry here. They went to Lerwick and got married and then came down and had a tea or something, that was all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 I've heard about the Shetland weddings, do you remember one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No, I never was at the Shetland weddin
g, never. Not when I was a boy. There - for a long time there were no - weddings was very quiet affairs. They just went to - they very often went to Lerwick and got married there. Sometimes must to the Manse and got married by the minister and then just h
ad tea in one of the houses, maybe the bride's house. Until - but they had Shetland weddings before my time. Oh then they were big affairs and maybe had them for - going on for three days. Oh yes. But that's before my time, that. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 They would have dancing you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes, dancing and - yes, oh yes. That was before my time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Why do you think that stopped then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 I don't know. Why it stopped but - again - in the 1920's they started having not weddings like that, they had they're - generall
y in the - in the village hall. They married in church and then went to the - sometimes they were married in the hall but generally they went to church to be married and then had a - the reception in the hall. And - then danced maybe until - daylight in t
he morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Were funerals a big occasion or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No. They }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  apparently}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771  they}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
 used to a while back and maybe in some districts they are yet. But - it was just a very quiet affair, you - your friends and relatives something. Nowadays mainly they jus
t put up a notice that the funeral - maybe it might be in the paper, the local paper, but generally they put it up on the Post Office and the shop windows that the funeral will take place at Dunrossness church such and such a time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 There's not a big tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Oh no, nothing like - oh none at all. Oh no, not at all. But - I believe in - Yell - they still have refreshments at a funeral. Maybe wine and biscuits. But - at one time they used to have plenty of booze at a funeral, I even heard where they go
t so drunk that they set down the coffin and maybe had a fight. But that's a long while ago. I've heard stories about it, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Were they strict about mourning clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes. Yes. When I was a boy that all the nearest relatives were dressed in bla
ck and even the men with a dark suit would have a - a black crepe band round one of their arms, I forget whether it was the left or the right. Sometimes they would have a little square diamond sewn on black cloth on a - a lighter coloured suit. And wear t
hat for - oh maybe for a year or more. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 
And - black - ladies with black hats and - this was going to church or anything, they were always in - and a widow was always dressed in black ever afterwards except she married again. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
But they don't do }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 that}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  nowadays, 
they don't pay much attention to it. There's no mourning clothes. Like a - a man may wear a black tie for a long time. Such as his mother's die - dead, well might wear a black tie for six months or so. But that's just about all now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Would you go out very much to visit relations in other parts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Yes. But not so much nowadays as when I was a boy. Oh yes. You - you went - you - you would walk on a fine moonlight night maybe for two or three miles for your relations. I did it very often. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 You had a lot of relations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Yes, quite a few. And not only relations, acquaintances or - or chums that you'd been at school with. You used to go there in the evening and - well maybe about - leave home about six o'clock and come back again - oh maybe - near midnight. Oh very often.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 And }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 you\rquote d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  just chat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes. Maybe if it was a place where there were any music maybe had a musical evening, in my case like. And - I was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Was there music in quite a few of the houses of your friends?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes, well - yes, quite a few. And - might go play cards. Game of whist or something like that, not very often but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Was it usual to offer some drink or food if people called in or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Always food but never - never much drink.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 I meant tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Oh yes, tea, yes, you had - you come there and you had tea about eight o'clock and then you stay and had maybe something again before you left for home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 You just called in, you didn't have to say you were coming?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 That's right. Then - but 
now you never go anywhere except by special invitation. Yes, very seldom but you tell them, you let them know you're coming.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 It's a big change?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh it's changed yes. Yes, that was better days, you never - you'd be sitting at the fire in the eveni
ng you heard the door open and - somebody'd come in. We looked forward to that, you never knew who was coming in. But there's none of that now. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 You mentioned you went into Lerwick for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 those}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  markets, was there anywhere else that you would go for shopping or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did I mention about going to ....?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 You mentioned about the cattle?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh but that was local. Oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 I thought that was Lerwick?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh no, the - the - oh yes, there were a - just about a mile from here th
ere were a - there were a - a - a sort of a yard, stone built yard and there were a little hut there were the auctioneer stood in the door and - and all the cattle was - was - they had it twice a year in May and October when I was a boy. That was when we 
g
ot off from school you see. Yes, well that - that wasn't far from the school either. But it's not - that old school now is closed. It's been closed since last year, there's a new one now. All the old schools, there was five in this district and they're al
l closed now. They all go to this one. Oh yes, there - that was locally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did you ever go into Lerwick then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Once or twice in the summer holidays I might have gone with me mother once in the summer holidays for a week and stayed with an aunt, I h
ad an aunt and a grandfather in Lerwick, that was my mother's father. And - another time I went with me father and we stayed a week in the summer holidays. That was about all that I was in Lerwick while I was going to school that I can remember. Of course
 after I left school I was many a time in Lerwick and I still go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Your parents wouldn't go there to buy things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes they did. Oh yes. Occasionally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Those weeks you just mentioned the only times you went away for a holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 You didn't go for Bank Holidays for instance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh no. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 
You see, when we got our summer holidays that was good enough, we were free of the school - and we could go where we liked and there's a little lake up here at the back where we played, well, it
's about - a hundred and sixty yards from where we're sitting just now. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
A nice little place where we sailed our boats and catched little fish, them little sticklebacks and - and - oh yes, we had a good time up there. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 That would be the summer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 This was summer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 And then in the winter evenings you would just call on people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Besides talking and music would they be working together, like mending nets and so on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Sometimes. They mended nets here, my father, but they had a
 place in the - next door up in the - up in the - we called it the loft but it was - yes, they mended the nets up there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Can you tell me about the place where the young men went?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 That was the old cobblers. Well there were two - I can just rememb
er one of them and he was a very old man when - when I can remember but he was still a - he was still making shoes and he made - after I started going to school I've seen me father go along, this - his name was Irvine and yet a message for a pair of new s
h
oes. Hand made, they lasted about a year but we were very - we go kicking stones on the road and they soon got holes on the - but they were very strong. And - but - when my father was young then they used to gather there about the evening, that was a favo
urite place, they might - they came from - miles around and they gathered in here beside this - there were two brothers then making shoes and mending shoes and they - all the youth gathered in there to - have }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 great arguments}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  like oh they're on about this and that and so on. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did they argue about politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
I suppose politics, religion, anything somebody would start an argument about - I've only heard them talking about it but - even when I started going to school there were still some of the -
 older boys called along there in an evening but - I never was there. Never. I was too young.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Was your father interested in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 politics}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well sort of way he was maybe but - I don't think he was just very -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Not active in anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No. No, he wasn't active about that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Do you know what his views were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well at that time I think it was Liberal. There were the - there were the Liberals and the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 Tories}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  and the - most of the people around here as far as I can make was all Liberals. No, no, there must have been }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 Tories}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  as well for there were plenty of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 private}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  enterprise so - but - I - I wasn't interested in that at the time and - hardly knew what the Liberal meant and what the Tory - meant, Conservative. And then - socialism only started u
p, when, in the 1920's or something, here anyhow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did the lairds put any pressure on people to vote the way they felt?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well - they may have done a while back, a hundred years or more, but I never heard of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Can you tell me about how Sundays were different, did you have to wear different clothes on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Yes, you had your Sunday clothes and when I was a boy we had to go maybe twice to church and then to once to Sunday school for a time and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Which church was that, the parish church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well my parents went to the - to the United Free }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14229023\charrsid12668771 C}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 hurch but my grandfather and grandmother went to the parish church, that's the Church of Scotland, and he was an elder. But - this United Free Church, it closed in about 1927, they amalgamated
 with the Church of Scotland and my parents were given - well I don't think ever they went much to church after they closed the - shut down the old Free - old Free Kirk as they called it. I don't think ever he went much after that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did they think it wrong to work or play on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Well we played on Sunday, we got away out of sight and played on Sunday but maybe we weren't supposed to do it, they were - a lot of things you weren't supposed to do on Sunday at that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh no work, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 excepting}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
 necessary, where you had - a few cows and they had to be fed. But it was nothing like - what it was in the Western Isles. I think you should read that book by Lilian Beckworth. The Hills is Lonely. The Sea for Breakfast. They're quite good
, I've read them all. And there - there's something about Sundays there and how they spent - they were - they were very strict there. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Was the church an important centre for social activities?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 It was sometimes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 What sort of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well - you mean social activities such as - concerts, yes, sacred - sacred concerts, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 cantatas}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 , sacred }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 cantata\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  and - well it was all sacred, there were no, what do you call it - secular, that's the word. You see, I'm a bit of a rationalist myself you see. Yes. Always been since I left school, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did you not like your Sunday school then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh I went to Sunday school, yes. And - like - we always get back to - all this came up, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 Dorothy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  and I went. I never learned very much, I never c
ould - I listened to the preachers and - but - somehow I - and I'm the same yet. I suppose I may be wrong I don't know but I'm kind of a free thinker or a rationalist or whatever you want to call it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Where do you think you got those ideas from, was that as a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Yes, well I just start thinking for myself and I couldn't see through - read the Bible and thought some of it was rather far fetched and - about old Noah and the ark and Adam and the apple and - all that things I think well, it might be 
true it be no, I'm not sure. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 Yes, that was - it was, I just - I have listened to the - like Omar Khayyam and when I - when I first read his Rubaiyat I think that something like myself. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 He says, strange is not that if the meerrieth who before us pass the do
or of times through, not one returns to tell us of the road which to discover we must travel. And you know it as well as me so I -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 As a boy did you have arguments about religion with other boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 We never had many arguments about religion and ye
t - even I now - I - I hardly ever argue about religion. I leave it to everyman's - he thinks what he likes. And - I have been around a bit and I've been with - and sometimes I found that - the best friends I have met had no religion at all and some that 
were very religious were - religion is one thing and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 Christianity}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  is another thing. That's how I look at it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 You like the ideas of morality but you don't like the church as a sort of organisation
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 I think the - you'll probably find in a dictionary
 a free thinker is one who rejects authority and religion. Well I - I agree with that. But - remember - you mightn't find many around here like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 In your family did you have family payers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No, not very often. My father was rather religious b
ut he wasn't strict. My grandfather, and I was only seven years old when he died, he was - I believe he was stricter with his family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Were you taught to say prayers at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well we had my mother learned a little rhyme about now I lay me down t
o sleep, I pray the Lord my soul to keep, have you ever heard that? Well that's what would happen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 What about grace at meals, did you say that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Not very often. Sometimes my mother would say God grant us a blessing. That was all. But they were - they went to church school and they -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Was there a temperance club attached to the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No. There were sort of a temperance - now what would they call it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Band of Hope?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 It was mainly for the ladies. They were initials, what was it, 
British Women's Temperance Association, B.W.T.A. But I don't know if there's anything of that now. Temperance - there maybe.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 the roads couldn't stand up to motor transport, mind that days it wasn't tarred surfaces, it was just gravel - just - you ca
ll it a dirt track nearly it was - and there were a few cars. There -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14229023\charrsid12668771 well}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
 there were several cars in Lerwick but I think there were only two down here in Dunrossness. And now nearly everybody's got their own car, it's nothing but motor transport, this is 1919 is - fifty-one years ago. Fifty-fifty-one years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 I suppose the first motor cars, the horses were terribly frightened of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes they were and people carting their peats home in the summer time used to go - leave home maybe about midnight s
o that there were no traffic on the roads, because the horses when they met a car they would, some of them, well they weren't all like that but there were some that were very frisky and they would maybe run, hack and go - go in the ditch and - oh yes. I c
a
n remember - you could - going - to bed hearing the rattle of the old horse and cart on the roads. Midnight, even eleven o'clock at night when there - there was no traffic. Now - nowadays there's traffic all the time, you've got it all the time, all hours
 of the night but - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Could you tell me about getting the peat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Well - every house had this piece of - we called it moor. You was set off maybe thirty yards by eleven. Well that's still the case. Maybe further back they had as much as they lik
ed, I'm not sure about that. And they would start - some would start in April, some in May, to cut out this peat with an implement they called a tusker. And they would lie for a fortnight or three weeks, depending on the weather, until they'd got - you se
e
, when the peat was new cut it was sort of soft, you couldn't handle it, it was wet and soft. And - it had to lie for a fortnight or three weeks depending on the weather and then they were set up on end for a time to dry in the sun and wind. And for a - o
h
 maybe a fortnight again depending on the weather. And then they were turned around with the other end up and - until they were thoroughly dry and then if they were - up in the hill you see they had to be brought down to the road and there were - generall
y
 brought down in a - what we called a sledge, it had two runners just like a - a - they just - there were not wheels you see, just steep and the horses pulled it down to the road then pulled the empty one up again. And if there were at the other sided of 
t
he road further down then - they would either - if they could get the cart to where the peats were then they were carted up but they only took maybe only half a load. And if the cart couldn't get there they were brought up on a wheel barrow to where the c
art could get them. And then they were carted home, some had to go maybe - cart them for - oh maybe six miles, five or six }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 miles}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 . We had about four miles and - down there at - in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 Sumburgh}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
 area and Virkie they had - two or three miles more, eight miles, so they took them quite a long distance.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 I thought the kishies were used for carrying peats?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 They didn't run a club for boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No. No, never had that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Were there any other sort of clubs here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 Well - when I was - before I left sch
ool there were a schoolmaster at the Quendale schools, this was after the '14-'18 war, and he started a club which he called the Dunrossness Young Men's Association. I learnt the self defense, I learned a bit about that, and the games - the game that I li
ked best was draughts, there were several draught tables, we did - there were no - there weren't supposed to be cards to be played in this central public hall - in case - they started gambling. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 But draughts was all right. And they had several - they were a 
table about this size with the draught board in it - so they could do - there were maybe four tables. No there were two tables with four draught boards. And I liked that game. Nobody plays it now but it's a good game - chess.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 You play chess do you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Well - I played mainly draughts but I could play - I never got very far - because there was nobody had to play. But oh chess is a - a great game. Yes. Oh it's a great game, but even draughts is a good game. That's a nice game that and a very interestin
g game and you can - but - this went on for - maybe - two seasons, two winters you see, it starts here November the twenty-first 1919 and - it's every week and you get - lectures on different subjects like - migrations - migration of birds. And here's one
 which I always remember, it was on the 19}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \super\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
 of December 1919 and there was a lecture on the possibilities of motor transport by George R Goudie, and George R Goudie was a motor mechanic. Now, in 1919 there were only one or two cars here - private cars. All
 the goods and feeding stuff and coal and - cement or anything came from Lerwick down here by boat. By a boat, and was landed at the pier. And - they brought it down by boat and then it had to be carted - well - the boat came down from Lerwick, it couldn'
t
 get into this pier, it had to anchor a bit off and then all the goods were put ashore with a small rowing boat. It was loaded in this was a derrick, rowed ashore, it wasn't very far. And then - there was a slip at the side of the pier, this boat came alo
ngside and the stuff was put up there and then it was wheeled up on a sort of a trolley and put in the store at the top - at the head of the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 pier}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 . But - and then they started carting this to the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 grocer\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
 shops and the baker was there for his flour and - sac
ks of flour and - they came from, oh, as far as I suppose from three miles away, more than three miles away, horse and cart. Well - this evening when this talk was on the possibilities of motor transport, this George R Goudie, he was very keen on motor tr
a
nsport and - he thought that - the time would come when it would all be motor transport. And after - well, for instance he said it would - it would be quicker and it would be cheaper and so on. And after this lecture, the - there - there was a sort of deb
a
te and there were several that said it was impossible. For one thing it would be too expensive, the other thing Oh that's long ago, yes, long ago. Oh but - no, that's - that's long before my time. But I've heard - my grandfather, they had them - their - t
heir peat moor, their peat banks not very far from the sea and they went with a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 boat}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
. They carried them in a kishie to the I down to the shore, loaded them in a - they probably emptied the kishie in the boat and then they came - they had either sailed the b
oat or rowed the boat for about three miles to - and then carried them up to the house and - and stack them. They was all stacked outside in a square built stack, you can see - you can see several of them along the road yet. Oh yes. But - that's about all
 I ever heard of was my grandfather, they called it boating the peats.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Was there a lot of helping each other among the neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Much more than there is nowadays. Oh yes. When one - one man was finished his - or it maybe before he was finished
 he would go and help his neighbour. Maybe he would leave off his own work to help his neighbour, but we get on none of that now. You don't, no. Very - well, I just know one fellow who'll leave his own work to help his neighbour and he stays there on the 
Quendale side. He's about the only one who'll do it and if you have to get help nowadays you have to pay for it. But }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 them days}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
 they would come, if you were finished your job first you would go and help your neighbour, if he was finished first he would come and help you and that was all, was to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 What sort of things did they help with, the hay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
With the hay and with the corn and with lifting the potatoes and all the things they would help each other. Oh yes. Remember, they were bigger families then
 and there were more people in the district. And - well the social life is not what it used to be. The - well the youth - they have - dances pretty regular but - the old people hardly ever - I haven't been - I used to go and play at dances, play the fiddl
e but I haven't been now for a lot of years. I still go to this fiddlers - Shetland Fiddler's society, probably go next - tomorrow evening. If Tommy Anderson, you - you tell me he's back again so I didn't - I know he was away last week I know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Would they lend implements?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 If people were working for you, you would offer them food and tea?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh yes, they always got their food. Nothing else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Just friendship?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes. They wouldn't expect anything. You'd be highly offended if you offered them anything. Oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did your parents have sort of special friends among the neighbours or were they all friends together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well I wouldn't say that, there were some that }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 were more}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  friendly than others. But - as a rule they were - around about here they were all friendly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Would you say that in the district there were any people that were thought of as superior to the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh yes. Oh certainly. Well maybe he was a bit better off and better circumstances and more money a
nd he had a better house and just thought they were a bit superior to his neighbour. Oh there was quite a lot of that. Oh yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14229023\charrsid12668771 Depending}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  on the job he was working at and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Would that sort of person be stand-offish from the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Sometimes he was a bit stand-offish.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Were the people who owned shops on very much the same level as the crofters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No, they reckoned themselves superior to the crofters. Oh yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 And they'd try not to mix with them too much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well - they would
 maybe mix. Remember we were all - the - the shopkeepers children and the crofter's children were all attending the same school and - well you didn't think on it when you were -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did the parents mind who the children played with, they wouldn't say, you're not to play with so and so's children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
No. The only - instance I can think about was - sometimes there were children who weren't just the - altogether clean or - you know, they were - lice on them and my mother didn't like that at all and if she 
knew that you'd been in contact with any of - well then - then - oh you had to have your hair combed and she'd be rubbing in some stuff that she called pommet or something, some for - but I never - she - she had a - she loathed that - anything like that. 
But then I'm only speaking for myself you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Would those be poorer families do you think or was it just their way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Not always. Not always. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Would you call those rough families, was that a word you used or not?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes, we used the wo
rd. No, not - that's kind of difficult to explain. There were one lad that used to come along here and his parents was quite well off. But she always thought his ears weren't very clean. She didn't - yes, but that was - they weren't just I but that was no
thing. I can remember her saying, he hasn't washed his ears, inside his ears. She didn't like this.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Do you think if you were going to be respectable then }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 cleanliness}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  was really the thing that }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 counted most}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 It was the thing that counted most was c
leanliness. You could have a patch on the seat of your trousers and that - and that if you came to school maybe you fall and you - you would maybe get a tear on your trousers and you had to get it mended maybe a patch, maybe stitched up and - well - some 
d
idn't like this. But the trousers was maybe not very old when you tore it on a nail or a barbed wire fence or you fell and burst the knee, used a to when I was going to school you see, when I first went to school you generally wore sort of - what do you c
all the, knickerbockers, they button, they had a button below the knee. That was away back in 1912 and - or - yes, that was the kind and - then - if you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 fell}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  on the road and the first that happened you got a hole on the knee of your trousers and then you had to get a patch and - and - and came with a patch.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
But people weren't looked down on because they had to wear old patched clothes, because I've sometimes heard it said that being able to wear new clothes made people feel very superior?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 That's quite right. Yes, that was the same here. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Would the poorest people be cotters who didn't have crofts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well - I'm not so sure }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 about}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  that, sometimes when a man didn't have a croft he may have been working at some steady job where he had a
 - a - regular wage coming in every week while the crofter had to depend a lot on the seasons and - the sort of land he had. If it was poor land, well, he didn't do so well but he - oh he'd hard times but - of course most crofters was fishermen as well he
re and - sometimes - from the beginning of the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 century}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  they did quite well at the fishing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Would a man who was a craftsman, who had been apprentices, would he be regarded as rather superior or did you all feel you were craftsmen?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well - the most 
Shetlanders can turn their hand to anything and - there were men who - all the houses were stone built at that time, they don't build any stone - stone walls }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 now}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 , it's all }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 concrete}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
 blocks and cement and - but - but there were - lots of men who were stonemasons, they could build a good wall, for houses, they were building houses and then there were who could turn their hand to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 carpentry}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  and they could do the inside and roof the houses and - some could do the whole thing, even build the stone wall and do the 
finishing and the roofing and the all that. And then - there were roadmen who had steady job working on the roads. They would quarry out the stone and then they had - they had their little quarries all along the road where they would be standing with thei
r
 little hammers breaking up this stones, stone -; small pieces and then other places where it was a gravel pit and they would be quarrying out this and they would be working all the time. That - you have to watch this thing now - that Sinclair Mouat you c
an - his uncle stayed down here and he was a roadman. He had a croft but he worked on the roads, he never went to sea, never went to fishing, he - he worked on the roads all - until he - he was on old man. All the time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Were there any people so poor they had to be given parish relief round here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well never in my time, I believe }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 before}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  my time - there were some but - I don't know about parish relief. And old person, if they were able to do any work at all then they would go and help a - work for s
omebody and they would get - wouldn't get money but they would get maybe potatoes or - or meat, mutton or fish or milk and eggs, for their work you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 So the community looked after its own old people in that way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well - to a certain extent, yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 
But there was a - in Lerwick there was what they called the poor house where the very poorest - I don't remember anybody ever going there but - from here - but I mean this district, but there were some that had to go there to be looked after and I don't
 think it was - there - there's none of that now. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 There's several old peoples }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14229023\charrsid12668771 homes,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  where they come sort of they can't }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 look}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
 after themselves then they can go into this homes and - and they're well looked after. And this Fiddlers Society to which I belong 
to we visit all that old peoples homes in the winter time and give them a sort of a concert. And the hospitals as well. There - in Lerwick there's - I think three or four - the Oak, the Montfield, others - and then }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 there\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  the Gilbert Bain hospital and we go in the winter in December generally. Go and night each to them. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 Entertain}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  them, just entertain the old people and they }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 seem}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  to enjoy it. I've been doing that for several years now. But they all - look so - happy. And often I think - I'll be sitting ther
e and looking - playing away on that old fiddle and looking as this old people and I think, not be very long before I'm there myself maybe. Nobody to look after me, be quite happy. And some of these places, you can - you just stay there. You can go out wh
en you like and come back when you}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14229023\charrsid12668771  liked}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  and - but you - if }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14229023\charrsid12668771 
your}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  meals and your bed and that's your home and there's always looking after you. But - that is one of the big improvements on the old times. Oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Were there any sort of gypsies around?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 tinkers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 , oh yes, and there's still one - well, not tinkers now. They used to - the tinkers - what we called }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 tinkers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  they made - they had their camp or their tents at the roadside somewhere and they were a making tin cans and tin pails and - o
h but none of them now. Of course most of the pails and cans you have now are plastic. But - oh yes, I remember that and - but they - they used to come round with their - with their pony and cart with goods like cups and saucers and that }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 kind}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  of stuff and 
- and - but they come - there are two or three that come yet, they have a- oh they have a nice car now and - they come with clothing, mainly drapery.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 They used to come with clothing did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes - oh they still do. That's the only thing that y
ou get now. And then - at one time they'd come around with some sort of cheap jewelry and a lot of the old people - they always had }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 spectacles}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  and the old people didn't go to get their eyes - there }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 were nobody}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
 to test their eyes then, so they would get in 
this - he had a big suitcase with a lot of spectacles and they'd try them on and look at a book until they got a pair that they could read with and oh that ones is all right, and they probably paid a shilling for them. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 Steel - small steel rims. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes, that w
as the kind of thing that used to be. My grandmother, she had that kind and the funny thing, my grandmother, when she was about seventy then she was using this spectacles to read with this bought from one of them tinkers. But she lived 'til she was over n
inety and by that time she could read without spectacles. She didn't need them. I don't know why.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Was there anyone came round selling things on the hire purchase system, weekly payments?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No. No, I never remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 What about savings clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Not in olden times. Never heard of that in olden times but there's plenty of that now. Oh yes. I - I - not hire }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 purchase}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 , you pay by installments, oh there's a lot of that. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Do you think that people then felt resentful about the hardness of the life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Some did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 How did you feel about it yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh it didn't worry me at all. I've always been sort of content, well I wouldn't say contented but - got on all right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 You didn't feel that it was wrong that you had to work so hard to make ends meet while any other people had it easy?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Well sometimes but - I was glad to be able to work and I went to sea and I was around and saw a lot and always saw somebody that worse off than myself and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 In Shetland at that time were there lairds around who seemed to be living in a very wealthy way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh yes, the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 lairds}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  one time, the laird and the minister they worked together. The minister, he - he preached that you had to do what the laird told you to do and - at that time - before - 1886 the tenants of crofts had no security of }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 tenure}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  and if they displeased the laird he could - they }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 called}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  it the evictions - they could - he told him out you go and you had to go. But after 1886 they that was what they called the crofters' co
mmission and they got a security of tenure so that the laird couldn't put them out as long as they could pay the rent. I don't know what happened if they couldn't pay the rent, I never heard of any cases like that because the rents - the rents weren't ver
y much - they weren't - very much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did you see less of him after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Oh yes, he stayed around. But he - he had - he couldn't interfere. And you see, before this, when you had no security of tenure you didn't have any incentive like to improve y
our buildings or anything like that because you didn't know when you might have to go. But after you got the security of tenure they improved their buildings, they improved their houses, they improved land and - and - and in that case is getting better al
l the time. And if you want now you can buy your land.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Who was the laird around here then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 It was always Bruce and it still is.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Where does he live?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 He - well - where he lived then was down there at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 Sumburgh}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 , it's a hotel now, the Sumburgh hotel. Well that was the laird's - where he stayed. Now he - he stays at Sandwick at - at Sandlodge, Sandwick. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 But - the old lairds - well there are plenty of books about the evictions and - yes, you've read about it.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Would you say then that the laird and the minister were the most important people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
they were. They were. And the people - they wasn't - so - they - they didn't have much education. But mind, that's a while back. They maybe could - a lot couldn't either read nor write. And - of c
ourse the minister, he was a very important person and the minister and the laird, they were - working together but - the minister told them they would have to do what the - what the laird said or else they would end up in hell fire. Oh.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 You've heard him preaching a sermon saying that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Well there's some of this when I was - I never go to much of that - to any of that now but - I - I - when you were a boy you got maybe not the - the resident minister but there were evangelists coming and they wou
ld preach nothing but hell fire all the time and they played on the emotions and it put some people who were very near daft they were. Yes. Quite a few - that went off by the - them }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 
evangelists}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  preaching hell fire and they - they didn't know - but - there's not so much of that now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Were you expected to raise your cap when you saw the laird or did you never see him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well I hardly ever saw him when I was a - I never saw a laird when I was a boy. No. You had - when - when - after I left school - you
 see, you paid your rent every November, your rent was due on the 11}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \super\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
 of November. And - now the laird - comes - to some house in the district and you go there to pay your rent. But - we used to - you never hardly saw the laird, he had his factor and you 
went to his - down to his office and paid your rent and I used to go after I left school, me father would send me with the rent sometime in November. There was a special day set for it. The 11}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\super\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  November unless it fell on a Sunday. But - they wasn't just v
ery fussy about that, if you were a day after or a week after, or you could even post it if you didn't and we very often did that. Posted it to him, posted it to the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 laird}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  himself. You got a receipt back. Then you were 11 right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 There's a phrase that is often }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 used in}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  England, I don't know if you use it, a real gentleman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Oh yes, a real gentleman, I used that expression myself. But - that doesn't mean a laird, what I mean by a gentleman is a - a - is a fellow who would - well a real good fellow th
en who would do - you a good turn anytime and - yes, oh that's what I call a real gentleman, doesn't matter about his religion, his worth anything, as long as he's a good fellow he's a real gentleman. That's what I mean by the term real gentleman. But I k
now what you mean as well. The gentleman, the laird, he was a gentleman, yes. He was supposed to be a gentleman. And - oh he was above all the rest, he - to the - old people, the laird, he was next to God, oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did he ever give things away to people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
The laird? Never that I heard of. And - a long while back they had to do with some of their produce to the laird, poultry, I've heard my uncle, that was my oldest uncle, he - when he was a boy, having to go to the laird with some poultry. And 
they called it - there was something that had a name for it, giving the laird - yes, oh yes. They went and they had to give so much to the laird. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Rather like the tithe?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well that was it. That's the word I think. I think so. Well it's long
 before my time. And again, the - they - they had to fish - the fishermen had to fish to the laird. The laird had a - had a shop where you could get all your stores and - you sold your fish to the laird, but you got no money, you just had to take it in ki
nd, in goods. And if you had a poor season and got in debt with the laird then you were - finished.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 He didn't own the mill did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No. The laird didn't own the mill here. The mill was at Quendale, it was privately owned but - it didn't belong to the laird.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Isn't there another mill towards Lerwick from here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 That's an old Shetland mill, Shetland water mill.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 But you didn't use that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 That's still in use, but - well, it's not used - it was in use until - well it was in use two ye
ars. But that - that's a Shetland water mill, a small thing, but this one here at Quendale is a big water wheel and - it was a big - but - maybe at one time there was a laird at Quendale as well and I belong to a Archeology and Natural History Society as 
w
ell as the Fiddlers Society and - we went to the Quendaye mill last June I think, because a lot of people, a lot of the members of the society have never seen it and Tom Henderson, him at the curator of the museum, he's a great friend of mine and we go ar
o
und a lot together. He's left here now you see, he was staying down here 'til a few weeks ago and now he's got a house in Lerwick, so I don't see so much of him now. But - this - mill - it belongs to the farmer there at Quendale now. Well I think it must 
h
ave - there were a laird at Quendale away maybe a hundred and fifty years, near two hundred years ago. The Quendale Estate and the Sumburgh Estate were - were separate, but now they're all one. And - this fellow that owns the farm he told us when this mil
l was built it was away back in 17 something. He give us the date. I just forget that at the moment. I didn't think it was so old as that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 But that's the one you sued anyway?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes, when I - after I left school we went to that mill with horse and c
art with corn and when it was ground then you went and brought it home and - oh yes, we had our own oat - oatmeal and - yes. But that mill has been out of use for over twenty years now. Except maybe the farmer uses it to - for - for his own use, like for 
- not grinding corn but for sort of bruising the corn for - feeding for the cattle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Was there a policeman in the parish?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 There were none here, well there are none here yet. There's only in Lerwick. But when I was going to school there were one s
tationed in Sandwick, that's about eight miles from here and he used to come down around }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 on a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
 pushbike. That was all the policeman ever I saw when I was a boy. But there's - there's not even one in Sandwick now, that's - but there - you see, they have thei
r police cars and their - oh they've come past here many a time for Lerwick. Car with police on it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 They didn't have much to do down here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well it's mainly motoring offences and drunken driving and breathalyzer and all that. Just the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 usual}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  - the same as it is all over. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
If there was somebody in the district that the people disapproved of very strongly did they have a special way of sowing it like in England we have something called rough music, does that mean anything to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Rough music? No. No, I've never heard of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Or putting somebody in Coventry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No, I know what you mean - I know what you mean by that but - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 If there were some people in the district who were rather a nuisance they were just tolerated were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Well maybe one or two - there weren't very much of that here. There were an old man who used to live not very far from here, the ruins of his house there yet. He was a very superstitious and - and didn't like to see anybody walking across hi
s ground or anything like that, he'd come out - of course I can remember him, he would - but he was just - he was - something wrong with him, he was kind of - he wasn't normal anyhow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 This was your grandfather's croft before your father's?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 When your father took it over your grandfather really retired?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh, he was - my - my - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 belonged}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  to my grandfather. He died then it belonged to my uncle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 When did he die?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 My grandfather? In 1913. And then it belonged to my uncle an
d he died in 1920. And then it was me father's, from 1920 and he died just four years ago, 1966. And then it came - just as - well there were no - I just informed the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 laird}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  that my father was - dead and he made everything all right, I'd no bother at all, no bother, he didn't alter anything, just went on, he just put it in my name instead of me father's that's all.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 So in 1911 your father would have been helping your grandfather?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes. He was helping me grandfather. And - and me uncle and - going -
 me father and me uncle was going in the fishing boats. Two uncles - two uncles. One of my uncles, he didn't stay here, that uncle stayed in the Quendale side at that time. He was married and had his family at - on the Quendale side and - and he was the s
kipper of the boat and then my uncle and my father and another three, there were six that went in the boat. And then me father, he worked on the croft and he did general work and so on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 And until your brother left school you worked here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 I - yes,
 that's right, I couldn't get away from away, I would like to get away to sea but I had to stay until me brother left school. And I carted peats and I went to the mill with the corn and I worked on the croft like - did a bit }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9046974\charrsid12668771 of ploughing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  and - and cutting corn and - working the peats like and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Then he stayed here after that did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
He stayed here and I went to fishing and another kind of fishing and was away for the whole week you see. In a herring fishing boat. I went five years, two years as a
 boy and then three years as a deck hand. And then after that I went to - but my brother, he married and after he married he didn't stay here. He stays about half a mile along the road. He -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Is he a crofter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes. He looks after the - the new school. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Then you went on the boats, after that did you come back to the Post Office?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Oh, that was only after the war, 1947 and - well I had relieved the old postman for a time and then when he retired, he was - he was an old man then, they ask
ed me if I would - well, in fact, they asked - there were another postman who retired and they asked me if I would take the job on and I wasn't very particular at the time, I didn't sort of fancy a postman's job at that time and I refused this job and - b
u
t that was after I had relieved - had relieved the - the postman on the round that I'm still doing for a few weeks yet. And then the other postman, he - well he didn't retire, he just - sort of gave it up. I think he had to leave it to look after his old 
p
eople. It was him that lived in the old house that you see that I pointed out to you down here. And they asked me if I would take that job and - I didn't think it was hardly worth me while so I refused and so the post master, the sub-postmaster, he got a 
-
 another fellow to take the job and he had it for several years, and then he left the district. And then this - this time - and this time - this is after - this is after 1945. Then - he - he left and he went to stay at Lerwick, that's on the road from her
e
 to Lerwick and he got a postman's job there. And - this old postmaster, he asked me again if I would take it and I still refused, and he got another fellow. That was the fellow, he only was here a short time and then he had to leave it. And then the post
m
an who was on this round that I am been on for twenty - twenty-four years nearly now - he - he retired and this sub-postmaster he sent for me. Would I take this job? Well, yes, I'll try it for a time. And I've been on it for twenty-four years, because I s
t
arted to like it, I thought it was a nice job. It was quite good and the pay was very good and it always got better. Wasn't so very much when I started and - but - I rather liked it so I just kept on until now I'm near sixty-five and talking about - well 
they're going to get it all motorized and take - lots of this little sub-post offices, they're doing away with them you see, all over the place and getting them all under one sort of centralization and motorization and - so - now - I'm finishing on the 25
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \super\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  of September and then -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 In the 1930's you were at sea the whole time really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
I was at sea, yes, and - but there were a time from - I went to sea for - I went to sea first in 1923. And I was five years and then in 1928 I was home for a bit, wor
k home around and - and I did some roadwork. And then I went away, went to South Shields. And I was away from home for two years and a half and that was in 1931 and that was the time when there were a depression all over and shipping tied up. Well I came 
h
ome and I was going to go again but I wasn't very sure for there were fellows going away and they couldn't get a job, they was coming back again. They were staying for maybe a month six weeks having to pay lodgings and - and - then they had to come home a
nd they were - well I was a bit lucky because - at that time, now I was always interested in archeology and down near }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5075252\charrsid12668771 Jamilshof,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  you've heard of that, you've been there. Well - they started excavating there and June 1931 and I'd been home for a few months t
hen and wasn't sure whether to go - where to risk going away and - I might have had no job go - well - this man, he wanted somebody to come and excavate, he wanted some men. And - I wasn't very sure, I'd been at sea for a while and - yet I was interested 
i
n archeology, so I went down and all. I was twenty-five years old then. And here'd this foreman come to start the thing and I went down on - on me bike and spoke to the man, I said, I believe you need somebody to - you're needing somebody to excavate here
?
 Yes. Any chance of a job? Oh yes, yes, how old are you? I said, I'm twenty-five. He said, that's just the right age. He said, you're not too old, you're not too young, when can you start? I said, this was on a Friday, I can come any time. Well, he says, 
c
an you be here Monday morning. And I got so interested in this excavations and I worked for two or three summers. And I - I - I - in fact it was only came to be only sort of seasonal work. One summer I was twenty weeks. And oh it was all right, I enjoyed 
m
yself. But then they closed down say in September and that year I think it was October and then I just did odd jobs in the winter time. Then after I time I thinks, well this is not going to get me very far, I went to sea again, so that was about - and the
n I've had the postman's job for near - well I've been in it twenty-four years but I'd been relieving for a -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 When you were in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5075252\charrsid12668771 Shields}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  were you working on the ships then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh that was a shipping port, oh no, they weren't because - you was on a tanker all round the - like round the - we went - that was my }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5075252\charrsid12668771 first}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
 ship that I was in, we left the Tyne and we went out through Panama and we went up along to California - we loaded oil there for - Buenos Aires, came all down along the West Coast through th
e Magellan Straits and - and back again, and back in again. And then the next time we went across to Japan and China and - we were in Borneo and we were in Australia, were in Bombay, India and all - all round. Over the years and that - when I came back an
d
 went in another one, went out to Australia and came back from Australia and - I stayed in the ship again and we did a trip up Buenos Aires again. From there to Mauritius. From Mauritius we loaded sugar for Montreal. We went on a reef in Montreal in the r
iver, up St Laurence river and nearly had to stop the winter there because it freezes but we came back to Antwerp with - with grain and - then I}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12668771  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5075252\charrsid12668771 was paid}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  off then, that was 1930 - that was when I came home. That was after that that I did excavations. And th
en I went again after and I was in a - a coaster for eighteen months and - then - it was the winter of 1935 - '30, no, '36 - '37. I was eighteen months in this one and then I left, I thought I would go deep sea because the weather was so bad around the Br
itish coast that winter and - then we were out in Japan and there were an explosion }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5075252\charrsid12668771 aboard}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
 the ship and I met with a bit of an accident, two or three of us were involved in this, we were blown up and I got this wrist broken, fractured and - I came home after that and I never was at sea again. Well not very much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did your sister stay on the croft?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Oh no, after she left school she got a job in the Post Office when she was maybe sixteen and she's there yet, and now she's fifty-nine nearly. She's been - she's been at the - she got a job in the Post Office.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did she marry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh yes, she's married, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 What does her husband do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well he - he - he's been a seaman but - he - for the last couple of years he got a job with the Air Ministry
 or with - no, it's the Ministry of - well, they go all around here and there on this sort of Air Ministry jobs, they - work down at the aerodrome and they work - well they've been at Lerwick, I hardly know what in, he always - he goes every morning. He l
eaves about the time I arrive there at the Post Office and he's - I'm back before him and - he gets Saturday off anyhow, but I never have Saturday off with the Post. Except now I have a fortnight's leave.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 In the old days on the croft who looked after the animals, was it the men or the women?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 I think we all did. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Who did the milking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Me mother generally. And - well me father - when I was away then me father and mother was all - well me brother was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5075252\charrsid12668771 for}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  a time but then he married and left, that was in the 1930's - 1935 and - me sister -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did your mother or grandmother spin or make cloth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 they did spin. Spinning for - for - spinning wool for knitting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Was that for the home - only?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Sometimes for the home for making }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5075252\charrsid12668771 stockings}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  but sometimes for - they sold them like - like - well shawls and - what they called spencers. This spencer was sort of an - of an under - underwear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 A long garment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well, I - I think it - I think that Kitty would be best one to tell you
 about the knitting for I don't know very much about it. You've got - you've got me now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 A sort of a long vest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh, aye, ayes. Yes, that's it. Well I couldn't - I wasn't very sure. A spencer. Oh yes, you had it, Winston Spencer }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5075252\charrsid12668771 Churchill}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 . I think it's the same word, I think it's spelled the same way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Can you remember there were ever sales of secondhand clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes, in Lerwick. Yes. Secondhand clothes, if sometimes got a secondhand shop where - but I - I never remember - buying anythin
g - secondhand.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 People didn't do that much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well - I - there's been more of that since the war, last war I think. Ex-Government stuff like - great coats and - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5075252\charrsid12668771 well}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  I've never had any of them.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 It's very common in England but it seems to be something people don't do so much up here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well not very much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 How much of an influence was your grandfather on you as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 My grandfather. Well my grandfather was a - was funny thing that, funny question. He was a very religious man, 
my grandfather. He wouldn't dream of doing anything sort of underhand or anything like that but he smoked a pipe all the time and I think that that was his influence on me for I'm still smoking a pipe. And I remember as a small boy - now mind I was only s
e
ven years old when he died - and he always smoked clay pipes, and he would go to the shop and he'd maybe get four for sixpence or four - a penny each or something, I - I don't know, money didn't - was no concern of mine then - and he would always give me 
o
ne when he came home, he'd have maybe four clay pipes and he'd give me a - a clay pipe, and I went around sucking this empty pipe, a clay pipe. But it always broke, I only had it for about a day then drip it and them clay pipes just went to pieces. And th
en - one day he come home with a - a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5075252\charrsid12668771 cherry wood}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
 pipe. That's a - a wooden pipe, they don't cost very much, they're just such a cut off a cherry tree and the stem in the same, just a little bit of a branch and bored through and - he - he bought me one of th
em I know, this was unbreakable you see. I know I was proud of this pipe and - they had a sort of a lid - a tin cover that they put on and I don't do any of that now, I never use that. But - oh I thought that I was - a man then, I'd got a real pipe that c
o
uldn't break. And the funny thing was, I never - a fellow, a young fellow, a good few years older than me, he wanted to have a look at this pipe. I was going around a wee boy with a pipe stuck in me mouth. He wanted to have a look at. That's a grand pipe 
you've got. And - and he drew my attention to something else, something aside and I went to look. When I turned back he was gone, I never saw the pipe again. He kept it. But - that - you asked about the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5075252\charrsid12668771 influence}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  my grandfather had on me, and it's all I can think about is a pipe.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did you spend much time with him playing when you were small?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
I - well, he was working around, he's an old man over eighty when he died and - but he was - in good health and working around the croft and I very often went with him and followed him round.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 You were fond of him then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh yes, he was nice old fellow, oh he was very good to me and me grandmother and all, yes. Oh yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 And the uncle was a bit of a teaser you said?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 He was - oh but he was good to us but he was a bit of a humourist. And he thought to play tricks, you know what I mean, he would - yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 When the adults were talking they didn't mind having children around?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well they told you to keep quiet sometimes but I suppose that 
- is usually when you - oh yes. Sometimes we were a bit rowdy and kicked up a din but - but - but you're thingummy's not running. I thought - I thought you had -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did you ever have any pocket money as a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes. A little not very much. You got m
aybe a sixpence now and again and a few - a few coppers and - maybe if it was your birthday you - if you were lucky you got half a crown and - and a shilling or so. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Before you went to school were you given in lessons in reading?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes. Got a 
little book and were learnt the alphabet and I remember - a sort of a card and it had the alphabet in capital letters and - and other letters, small letters and in the centre was a dial of a clock with tin hands that you could move around for the time and
 you learned the alphabet and you learned the times so - I - when I went to school I could - knew the alphabet from A to Z and I also knew the time
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Could you read a little bit then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No, not very sure about the reading, maybe simple two letter words but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Your parents were very interested in what you did at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes, before I went to school we - they had - we learnt that and - maybe could count up to ten or twenty or something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Did your parents go to the school and meet the teachers and ask how you were doing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
No. My mother came, I was the oldest one in the family, and the first morning I had to go to school she came with me, and that was the only time they were ever at school. When my brother, he was two years and
 a half younger than me, when he was age for to go to school then I took him to school. My sister was two years and a half younger than that and she just came along with us and that was all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 She took an interest in what you were doing at school, she'd ask you how it was going?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
My mother? Well, yes, we - they didn't just pay very much attention and we did the best we could - we weren't - we weren't - very much annoyed about anything, we - we -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 But they were very ken that you should do well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
Oh yes, yes. Yes. We never got into very much trouble. Nobody at this local school, I never mind any - any bother there with anybody. When I started going there were about seventy on the register and - it always got less and less until - last year th
ere were maybe twenty, nineteen or twenty and then the old school, all the local schools were closed and - they built the new one and it was opened, the Queen was there on August last year and unveiled the plaque outside the door and they all go there now
. There's over a hundred going to that school. And they're - I think four teachers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 When you were at school you didn't ever have a part time job for earning any sort of money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No. Oh no, we had this croft here and maybe we'd - do odd jobs round t
he croft or - but nothing for money, we just did it mainly for the fun of doing it and of course we were - had plenty to eat and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Do you remember staying up late on social occasions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Somebody in or something like? Oh yes. Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 I think the children were able to join in more than they were in England.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 You wouldn't be packed off to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 No, we weren't packed off to bed, only during the week maybe we went a bit earlier to bed but then there were no school on Saturd
ay so Friday evening we stayed up late and Saturday then you went to bed early on Sunday to have to go to school again on Monday morning. But - it's much the same with me yet. I've been a postman for twenty-four years and - the last year we've had to get 
u
p earlier in the morning, the mail came down here earlier so that the alarm clock went off at half past five. Well I had to get to bed before midnight. But if there was anything special on, sometimes it may be one o'clock we went to bed and then you only 
had - four - maybe four hours sleep.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5075252\charrsid12668771 Mr Graham told us that sometimes in the Shetlands people had a big plate in the middle of the table called the trencher?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Do you remember that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well - this would be - in Mr Graham, he's younger
 than me. Could he remember that? Well - yes, but there's another thing that comes in there. Which I can't remember about and I don't think John Graham can remember either. They had a - a wooden box affair, they called it a trough that they used to set on
 the table with the potatoes, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5075252\charrsid12668771 but}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
 that's a long while ago. But - I can remember a big plate with the - with the potatoes, they were boiled with their jackets on and they were put on this plate and then you just stuck in your fork and you took one and you - 
yes, I remember that and In-fact I believe that's going on at the present day you see. The potatoes are all on this plate and - for - well, it's not very often that they boil them nowadays with their - in their jackets but - it is }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14229023\charrsid12668771 done}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771  occasionally and the
n they're just all put on a plate and you - you'll maybe have a look around. Mind you I'm talking about - my own - my own home, have a look and thing that's a good one so you'll - you'll jab that one and - and then if the -- we used - it's our own potatoe
s you see and if }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5075252\charrsid12668771 there\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
 one that's not so good well it's just discarded and it goes to the poultry or something. See, after that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Do you remember having mattresses made of chaff?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 And they changed it, used to make a new one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 How often did they do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh - I couldn't tell you, maybe twice a year, I'm not sure about that, but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Were they comfortable?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well - I can remember this mattresses filled with straw. And they were - I liked them better. No - I 
went to sea and you always when you were going on a voyage you bought a - a mattress filled with straw. You could buy it at any shipping port in a seaman's outfitter, you get this one for the voyage and - when your voyage was finished you dumped it and wh
e
n you went again you bought a new one and I think they cost maybe half a crown. And they were just - oh you get that in any - I don't know - of course nowadays it's all different, I haven't been to sea for a long while. But - I think it's all supplied in 
the ship, you don't - the sailor at that time, way before the war, he had to look out for his own clothing and his own - bedding Mattress and all. And pillow and everything. But now it's all supplied in the ship as far as I know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Do you remember double-decker beds?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Oh yes. Kind of bunks. I don't think there's any now but I remember us having here. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Can you describe how they were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Well - they were just - four posts or uprights and - and the - they were - wooden beds and the - the - 
and the beds was all joined to this uprights and about maybe three foot or something above the under one there were the same again. And I have seen them sometimes with a small step, well steps, fast to the side so that they could climb up. But we didn't h
ave that for I remember, I remember sleeping in the upper bunk and of course I could jump up in it and I liked - I liked that one. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 That's different from a box bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 Yes, oh it wasn't a box bed, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2637051 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 A box bed folds into the wall does it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7105026 RB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8352648\charrsid12668771 
No, the box bed was just like a - I cannot very well describe this, it was just a big box with an opening in the side in the - the - there were - the bottom was wooden boards and then the mattress was on top of that but the bottom was - just a usual 
height from the floor. And then the whole thing was boxed in, even canopy over the top and - and a sliding door at the side.
